description:
Phase 1: Preparation & Assessment (January - March, 2023)
- Onboard a restoration and reforestation lead; 
- Assess the characteristics of the site (soil, vegetation, fauna, topography, climate);
- Define the roles and responsibilities of the various players involved over the long term;
- Define a complete protocol for the preparation, planting, and maintenance of the plants until the objectives are achieved, with a strategy for sustainable protection against illegal logging, fire, and livestock grazing;
- Define the management plan for the reforested plots, specifying the maintenance activities, the entities responsible over time, the products harvested or not (fruit, firewood, timber, non-wood products), the cutting rotation, and the economic model;
- Define an optimal calendar based on the rainy season, and stick to this calendar to maximize the chances of success for young plants;
- Draw up a site development and maintenance plan (choice of species, soil preparation, planting, layout and density of trees, watering, protection, creation, and maintenance of firebreaks);
- Take into account previous and current projects and initiatives in the intervention area - analyze their successes and failures and capitalize on the lessons learned from these experiences;

Phase 2: Stakeholder engagement (February - March, 2024)
- Identify the skills needed to ensure the success of the project and ensure that those involved, including local communities and stakeholders, have the required skills or have received training;
- Ensure that training courses include maintenance, monitoring, and evaluation, an understanding of the services provided by trees on a landscape scale, and knowledge of the relevant legislation.
- Consult other relevant stakeholders (local authorities, other NGOs, private sector, civil society organizations, spiritual and traditional leaders);
- Ensure that the objectives and strategy reflect these consultations, meet the primary needs identified (well-being, decent income, food security, access to education, etc.), and make the most of local know-how;
- Ensure that the people reforesting have a concrete and established interest in doing so in order to ensure that they can take ownership of the initiative. 

Phase 3: Preparatory Activities (March - June 2024)
- Mobilize resources, including human labor, equipment, and materials;
- Find or create training materials adapted to the target audience, in particular, visual aids in the case of illiteracy;
- Ensure that reforestation is carried out in synergy with the other components of the landscape (agriculture, livestock farming, tourism, infrastructure, etc.), particularly through local planning.

The project’s main activities include:
1.	Conducting the project baseline to document the starting point of project implementation;
2.	Site and nurseries identification;
3.	Geodata collection and shape files production of sites;
4.	Awareness creation among communities;
5.	Establishment and management of nurseries;
6.	Capacity building of beneficiaries on nursery management;
7.	Sites preparations;
8.	Plantation of trees;
9.	Trees maintenance
10.	Joint project activities monitoring
The plantation will start on 15 September 2024 and end  31 December 2025, while the tree maintenance will continue until  end October 2029.

